<main class="page">

  <section class="cover">
    <p class="cover__eyebrow">For residents, council-watchers &amp; First Nations on the North Shore</p>
    <h1 class="cover__title">The Massey Solar Project in 2026: <em>what's been decided, what's still ahead</em></h1>
    <p class="cover__lede">Ahnii. A 141-megawatt solar farm has been proposed on about 600 acres eight kilometres northeast of Massey, in the Township of Sables-Spanish Rivers. It has split the township's council chambers, generated petitions with thousands of signatures, drawn the formation of a citizen committee, and — as of April 10, 2026 — been awarded a 20-year contract by Ontario's electricity system operator. It is also being built in partnership with two First Nations. Almost everything you hear about it is at least partly true. The reason the conversation feels confusing is that several different decisions are happening on different timelines, and several different governments hold authority over different pieces. This page holds them apart.</p>
    <p class="cover__byline">
      <strong>Put together by Russell Jones</strong> on behalf of OIATC, as a community resource. Russell is a member of Sagamok Anishnawbek First Nation, which neighbours the proposed project site. This page is not affiliated with Potentia Renewables, the Township of Sables-Spanish Rivers, the Massey Wildlife Conservation Committee, or any First Nation. Sources are linked throughout. If you spot something that needs correction, please get in touch.
    </p>

    <div class="stats">
      <div class="stat"><div class="stat__fig">141 MW</div><div class="stat__lab">Nameplate capacity</div></div>
      <div class="stat"><div class="stat__fig">~243 ha</div><div class="stat__lab">~600 acres, leased private land</div></div>
      <div class="stat"><div class="stat__fig">8 km</div><div class="stat__lab">Northeast of Massey</div></div>
      <div class="stat"><div class="stat__fig">20 yr</div><div class="stat__lab">IESO contract (Apr 10, 2026)</div></div>
      <div class="stat"><div class="stat__fig">≥50%</div><div class="stat__lab">Indigenous equity</div></div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>The bottom line</h2>
    <div class="bottomline">
      <p>Municipal support for the Massey Solar Project is in place, and the Independent Electricity System Operator (IESO) has awarded the project a 20-year contract under the Long-Term 2 procurement. The land is privately owned and leased to the developer, and the township's Official Plan and zoning bylaw permit a Class 3 solar facility in this rural zone.</p>
      <p>The project is <strong>not yet approved</strong>. Before it can be built, it has to clear Ontario's Renewable Energy Approval process under Regulation 359/09 — the provincial environmental review, which includes formal public and Indigenous consultation. Construction is currently proposed for 2028 and commercial operation for 2029. Until those next steps happen, none of the substantive environmental or consultation questions are settled.</p>
      <p>The question of how meaningful the consultation will be — especially with <a href="https://www.sagamokanishnawbek.com/">Sagamok Anishnawbek</a>, whose territory the project sits in but which is not one of the two First Nation equity partners — is the most important thing to track from here forward.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Five things are happening at once</h2>
    <p>The reason this gets confusing is that five different things are in motion, each on its own timeline, each decided by a different body. Keeping them apart is most of the work.</p>

    <div class="parts">

      <article class="part">
        <span class="part__num">01</span>
        <h3 class="part__name">The project itself</h3>
        <p class="part__amount">141 MW · ~243 ha · 8 km NE of Massey</p>
        <div class="part__body">
          <p>The <a href="https://www.potentiarenewables.com/our-portfolio/massey-solar-project/">Massey Solar Project</a> is a proposed utility-scale ground-mount solar facility on roughly 600 acres of leased private land, about 8 km northeast of Massey and 90 km west of Sudbury. The developer is <a href="https://www.potentiarenewables.com/">Potentia Renewables Inc.</a>, a Toronto-based company wholly owned by Power Sustainable Capital Inc., an affiliate of Power Corporation of Canada. The project entity is Massey Solar Inc.</p>
          <p>Once operating, it is expected to power roughly 23,000 Ontario homes and offset about 3,500 tonnes of CO₂-equivalent per year. Construction is projected at about 18 months and up to 150 jobs; operations may last up to 35 years with a small on-site team.</p>
        </div>
        <p class="part__what"><strong>What it means for the North Shore</strong>The largest single-site renewable project the township has ever considered. Land use, jobs, tax base, water, wildlife, and Indigenous consultation are all in play at once — none answered by this one number.</p>
      </article>

      <article class="part">
        <span class="part__num">02</span>
        <h3 class="part__name">The municipal decision</h3>
        <p class="part__amount">Approved Aug 2025 · Reaffirmed Mar 25, 2026</p>
        <div class="part__body">
          <p>Council gave the project a Municipal Support Confirmation in August 2025, conditional on the farm not being built on land designated "prime" agricultural. That confirmation was a required input to the IESO procurement. On <a href="https://shorereport.substack.com/p/massey-solar-project-can-proceed">March 25, 2026</a>, after a motion to rescind, Council voted to keep the support in place — Deputy Mayor Mike Mercieca was the lone vote to rescind.</p>
          <p>Mayor Kevin Burke's position is that the township checked the proposal against its <a href="https://www.sables-spanish.ca/wp-content/uploads/2020/07/Final-Version-OP-May-28-2020_compressed.pdf">Official Plan</a> and zoning bylaw and found compliance: solar is a permitted use in the rural zone, and Section 3.11.4 commits the township to "promoting and supporting the development of renewable energy sources."</p>
        </div>
        <p class="part__what"><strong>What it means for the North Shore</strong>The municipal piece is effectively done. Short of amending the Official Plan to remove solar — which wouldn't undo a contracted project — the next decision points are provincial, not local.</p>
      </article>

      <article class="part">
        <span class="part__num">03</span>
        <h3 class="part__name">The IESO contract</h3>
        <p class="part__amount">Selected Apr 10, 2026 · 20-year contract</p>
        <div class="part__body">
          <p>On April 10, 2026 the IESO announced the winners of its <a href="https://www.ieso.ca/Sector-Participants/Resource-Acquisition-and-Contracts/Long-Term-2-RFP">Long-Term 2 RFP</a>. Massey Solar was one of <a href="https://www.potentiarenewables.com/2026/04/10/massey-solar-project-selected-through-ontario-lt2-procurement/">14 projects awarded 20-year contracts</a> (12 solar, 2 wind), about 1.3 GW total, priced roughly 21% below previous large-scale renewable contracts.</p>
          <p>Two LT2 features matter: Indigenous participation was heavily incentivized through rated criteria (all 14 winners hold ≥50% Indigenous equity), and a Municipal Support Confirmation was required at submission. Commercial operation must begin before May 1, 2030.</p>
        </div>
        <p class="part__what"><strong>What it means for the North Shore</strong>This is the moment that turned a proposal into a financed project. With a 20-year revenue contract and equity partners signed on, it has the resources to move ahead. Not yet permitted — but committed.</p>
      </article>

      <article class="part">
        <span class="part__num">04</span>
        <h3 class="part__name">The Indigenous partnership</h3>
        <p class="part__amount">Wahnapitae &amp; Atikameksheng · ≥50% equity</p>
        <div class="part__body">
          <p>Potentia says the project is being developed in partnership with <a href="https://www.wahnapitaefn.com/">Wahnapitae First Nation</a> and <a href="https://www.atikamekshenganishnawbek.ca/">Atikameksheng Anishnawbek First Nation</a>, who together hold at least 50% equity. Both are <a href="/explainers/robinson-huron-treaty">Robinson Huron Treaty</a> signatories whose reserves sit roughly 75–100 km east of the site, near Sudbury.</p>
          <p>What the partnership has not visibly addressed, as of May 2026, is the relationship to <strong>Sagamok Anishnawbek</strong>, whose reserve and traditional territory sit closer to the project. Sagamok submitted emailed objections about consultation in March; the Mayor also reported verbal interest from Chief Angus Toulouse in participating. Both can be true at once.</p>
        </div>
        <p class="part__what"><strong>What it means for the North Shore</strong>Wahnapitae and Atikameksheng as equity partners is significant. It does not, however, resolve the separate Crown duty to consult Sagamok and any other community whose rights may be affected.</p>
      </article>

      <article class="part">
        <span class="part__num">05</span>
        <h3 class="part__name">The provincial environmental review</h3>
        <p class="part__amount">Reg. 359/09 · Not yet started</p>
        <div class="part__body">
          <p>Before it can be built, Massey Solar must obtain a <a href="https://www.ontario.ca/page/renewable-energy-approvals">Renewable Energy Approval (REA)</a> under <a href="https://www.ontario.ca/laws/regulation/090359">Ontario Regulation 359/09</a> — the substantive environmental review, and the stage at which most current concerns are formally studied.</p>
          <p>The application must include a hydrogeological assessment, wetland and woodland evaluations, a Natural Heritage Assessment, a Species at Risk review, an archaeological assessment, and a noise study, plus formal public consultation (at least two meetings) and Indigenous consultation. As of May 2026 it has not been submitted.</p>
        </div>
        <p class="part__what"><strong>What it means for the North Shore</strong>The questions driving the local debate — the Aux Sables River and Massey's water, 200+ bird species, wildlife, herbicides, decommissioning — are properly addressed here, not at the municipal stage.</p>
      </article>

    </div>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Who decides what</h2>
    <p>Three governments and one independent agency each hold authority over a different piece. The municipal piece is local; everything substantive about whether the project actually gets built is provincial or federal.</p>

    <div class="deciders">

      <div class="decider">
        <h3 class="decider__name">Township of Sables-Spanish Rivers</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Confirms whether the proposed use fits the Official Plan and zoning.</li>
          <li>Issues (or does not issue) a Municipal Support Confirmation for IESO bids.</li>
          <li>Can revise the Official Plan and zoning going forward — but cannot retroactively undo a project that already has provincial approval and a signed IESO contract.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="decider">
        <h3 class="decider__name">Independent Electricity System Operator</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Runs the LT2 procurement and awards 20-year contracts.</li>
          <li>Sets the rules, including weighted Indigenous-participation criteria and the Municipal Support Confirmation requirement.</li>
          <li>Holds the contract and can enforce its terms — but does not regulate environmental impact.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="decider">
        <h3 class="decider__name">Province of Ontario (MECP)</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Issues the Renewable Energy Approval under Regulation 359/09.</li>
          <li>Reviews hydrogeology, wildlife, wetlands, archaeology, noise, and Species at Risk.</li>
          <li>Requires public and Indigenous consultation.</li>
          <li>Can refuse the approval, attach conditions, or require design changes.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="decider">
        <h3 class="decider__name">The Crown (Canada and Ontario)</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Owes a duty to consult Indigenous communities whose Aboriginal or Treaty rights may be adversely affected.</li>
          <li>That duty is not extinguished by an equity partnership with one or two First Nations; it is owed to each Nation whose rights are at stake.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

    </div>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>What's been decided, what's still ahead</h2>
    <p>Each new headline can read like a single decision is being made. It usually isn't. Here is the split.</p>

    <div class="columns">

      <div class="column">
        <h4>Decided</h4>
        <ul>
          <li>Municipal Support Confirmation: granted August 2025, reaffirmed March 25, 2026.</li>
          <li>IESO LT2 contract: awarded April 10, 2026 for 20 years.</li>
          <li>Indigenous equity partnership: ≥50%, with Wahnapitae and Atikameksheng Anishnawbek named.</li>
          <li>Official Plan and zoning: solar is a permitted use in the rural zone (Section 3.11.4, 2020 Plan).</li>
          <li>Site: ~243 ha of privately-owned, leased land about 8 km northeast of Massey.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="column">
        <h4>Still ahead</h4>
        <ul>
          <li>Renewable Energy Approval application and review under Regulation 359/09.</li>
          <li>Formal hydrogeological, wildlife, wetland, archaeological, noise, and Species at Risk studies.</li>
          <li>Crown consultation with Sagamok Anishnawbek and any other affected First Nation — distinct from the equity partnership.</li>
          <li>At least two public consultation meetings as part of the REA.</li>
          <li>A 2026 municipal election that could change council composition.</li>
          <li>Construction (proposed 2028) and commercial operation (proposed 2029; before May 1, 2030).</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

    </div>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>What's happened so far</h2>
    <p>A short timeline of the moments that matter most for residents.</p>

    <div class="tl">

      <div class="tl__entry">
        <span class="tl__date">1998</span>
        <div class="tl__body">
          <h4>Township of Sables-Spanish Rivers formed</h4>
          <p>Massey, Webbwood, The Spanish River, and the geographic townships of May and Shakespeare amalgamate, named for Massey's location at the junction of the Spanish and Aux Sables rivers.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="tl__entry">
        <span class="tl__date">2020</span>
        <div class="tl__body">
          <h4>Official Plan revision</h4>
          <p>Council adopts a Plan that recognizes climate change and commits the township to "promoting and supporting the development of renewable energy sources," including commercial-scale solar (Section 3.11.4). The Plan was due for revision in 2025.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="tl__entry">
        <span class="tl__date">2025-08</span>
        <div class="tl__body">
          <h4>Municipal Support Confirmation granted</h4>
          <p>Council gives Potentia's application its required Municipal Support Confirmation, conditional on the project not being sited on land designated "prime" agricultural.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="tl__entry">
        <span class="tl__date">2025-10</span>
        <div class="tl__body">
          <h4>IESO bid submitted</h4>
          <p>Potentia submits the Massey Solar bid to the IESO under the Long-Term 2 RFP, with Wahnapitae First Nation and Atikameksheng Anishnawbek as Indigenous equity partners.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="tl__entry">
        <span class="tl__date">2026-02-25</span>
        <div class="tl__body">
          <h4>Council debate begins</h4>
          <p>Deputy Mayor Mike Mercieca raises citizen concerns. Farmer Gary Vermeer questions the zoning interpretation. The Massey Wildlife Conservation Committee is publicly named for the first time.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="tl__entry">
        <span class="tl__date">2026-03-10</span>
        <div class="tl__body">
          <h4>Potentia responds publicly</h4>
          <p>Through a statement to Espanola's Moose FM, Potentia addresses groundwater, vegetation management, panel materials, farmland classification, and decommissioning, noting the REA process has not yet started.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="tl__entry">
        <span class="tl__date">2026-03-11</span>
        <div class="tl__body">
          <h4>Rescind motion blocked on procedure</h4>
          <p>An MWCC delegation presents to Council. Deputy Mayor Mercieca moves to rescind the August 2025 approval, citing emailed objections from Sagamok's Michelle Toulouse. The Mayor rules the motion out of order pending proper notice.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="tl__entry">
        <span class="tl__date">2026-03-25</span>
        <div class="tl__body">
          <h4>Council reaffirms support</h4>
          <p>After delegations, Council votes against rescinding; Deputy Mayor Mercieca is the only vote in favour. The Mayor says Council heard verbal interest from Sagamok Chief Angus Toulouse in his community participating.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="tl__entry">
        <span class="tl__date">2026-04-10</span>
        <div class="tl__body">
          <h4>IESO awards LT2 contract</h4>
          <p>Massey Solar is one of 14 projects (12 solar, 2 wind) awarded 20-year contracts. All 14 include ≥50% Indigenous equity. Total awarded capacity is about 1.3 GW.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="tl__entry">
        <span class="tl__date">2026-05</span>
        <div class="tl__body">
          <h4>Project in development phase</h4>
          <p>Potentia begins the development phase and publishes a project newsletter ("Massey Solar Project Pulse"). REA application not yet filed; construction proposed for 2028, commercial operation in 2029.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

    </div>
  </section>

