  <section>
    <h2>Key terms</h2>
    <dl class="glossary">
      <dt>Class 3 solar facility</dt>
      <dd>Under Ontario Regulation 359/09, a ground-mount solar generation facility with nameplate capacity over 10 kW connected to a transmission system. Massey Solar is a Class 3 facility.</dd>

      <dt>Commercial Operation Date (CoD)</dt>
      <dd>The date a project is contractually required to begin selling electricity to the grid. For Massey Solar, currently projected as 2029, with a regulatory deadline before May 1, 2030.</dd>

      <dt>Crown duty to consult</dt>
      <dd>The legal obligation on Canada and Ontario to consult — and, where appropriate, accommodate — Indigenous communities when a proposed Crown decision may adversely affect Aboriginal or Treaty rights. Triggered by the REA decision, not by the IESO contract or municipal approval.</dd>

      <dt>IESO</dt>
      <dd>Independent Electricity System Operator. Ontario's not-for-profit agency that operates the wholesale electricity market and runs procurements.</dd>

      <dt>LT2 / Long-Term 2 RFP</dt>
      <dd>The IESO's second long-term procurement, which awarded about 1.3 GW of renewable contracts in April 2026, including Massey Solar. Required Municipal Support Confirmation; heavily weighted Indigenous participation; all 14 awarded projects ended up with ≥50% Indigenous equity.</dd>

      <dt>Municipal Support Confirmation</dt>
      <dd>A document from a host municipality required for a project to bid into LT2. Sables-Spanish Rivers issued one in August 2025.</dd>

      <dt>Official Plan</dt>
      <dd>The municipal land-use planning document. Sables-Spanish Rivers' current Plan was revised in 2020 and was due for review in 2025. Solar is a permitted use in the rural zone under Section 3.11.4.</dd>

      <dt>REA / Renewable Energy Approval</dt>
      <dd>The provincial environmental approval required under Ontario Regulation 359/09. Includes hydrogeology, wetlands, woodlands, wildlife habitat, Species at Risk, archaeology, and noise studies plus formal public and Indigenous consultation. Not yet filed.</dd>

      <dt>Robinson Huron Treaty</dt>
      <dd>The 1850 treaty between the Anishinaabe of Lake Huron's north shore and the Crown. The project site sits on Robinson Huron Treaty territory. (See the OIATC <a href="/explainers/robinson-huron-treaty">Robinson Huron Treaty explainer</a>.)</dd>
    </dl>
  </section>

